Visible is a fine circumferential line, 'Imn and underneath a row of further hieroglyphs, the first being nfr, then maybe Hs? and a third illegible sign.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression showing two rows of basketry coil impressions at the rear and at the side a further row, meaning that this piece was positioned most likely on the lid of a basket. The fine brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica particles. The clay was hardened after excavation. The front shows one impression of a scarab-like seal, finger impressions around it. The seal impression shows a circumferential band that thickens in one part into a plant-like decoration in the upper right corner. On the left a falcon facing to the left, with a flagellum, right of it a small hippopotamus and on top of it a lying antelope or ibex with its head towards its back to the right. Underneath the hippopotamus and the falcon a lying crocodile facing to the left. The same motif is found on EA86925.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows a darker discolouration. The rear shows two coils of basketry on one side and one coil of basketry on a second side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. Recognisable is a djed pillar in the middle with cobras on each side facing towards the pillar. The same motif is found on EA86924.

description.value: Complete seal-impression with two rows of basketry coil impression at the rear and at the side one further rows of a larger size, showing that this piece was positioned most likely on the lid of a basket.  The fine brown Nile clay shows small inclusions of mica, some salt incrustations can be seen. The clay was hardened after excavation before the rear was cleaned properly. The top part shows the impression of an oval and elongated seal that possibly originates from a ring bezel and there are many finger prints around and on top of the seal impression, squashing quite a lot of the motif.  The seal impression is shallow but clearly cut and shows a circumferential band, inside one column of hieroglyphs facing to the left. The most upper sign is illegible, underneath an erected cobra (like I14 but with a shorter tail), on top of a horizontal line that could be an 'n', underneath another illegible sign, right of it a verticalstroke (Z1). Same seal as used on EA86709.

The front has a small flat area with downwards bent sides that are partly reshaped and therefore covered with finger prints. On the flat area part of an seal-impression. The same motif is found on EA86891, showing more from the lower part with hieroglyphs: 'Imn and underneath nfr qbH (W15) with water running towards the right and a small circle in the upper part.

description.value: Almost complete seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows one side with very clear impressions of two smaller rows of basketry coil and another side with one larger row of basketry coil, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side bears an impression of a quite large oval scarab-like seal and many finger impressions covering parts of the seal-impression. The motif shows a round sign, maybe a sun-disc and right of it possibly a scorpion, only body and tail are preserved, underneath a winged scarab, all surrounded by a circumferential line. Same motif as EA86798.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows a convex impression of a textile or leather object, probably a bag. Two thick impressions of a turned string with a width of 0.3 cm. At the convex upper side the upper half of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible, the sides are bending downwards and show many finger impressions. The seal shows a circumferential line, inside a seated falcon, it has both wings stretched in front of the body, is facing to the left and wears the double crown and a flagellum but with a slightly rounded end. The falcon is sitting on top of a nb-basket at the bottom. The lower part is not preserved but is shown in EA86941 and EA86950 which have the same seal. Black accretion on the surface.

description.value: Complete seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows one side with one coil of basketry and another side with a flat area with impressions of plant fibres which seem to be from a basket as well. At the bottom of the seal another lying enemy with its hands on the back. This seems to be the same motif as EA86753.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a slightly convex surface like from a leather bag, perpendicular to it two impressions of an unturned cord with a width of 0.2 cm in the break.
